# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The **Group of the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe** (**ALDE Group**) was the liberal–centrist political group of the European Parliament from 2004 until 2019 when it merged into Renew Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] ALDE was made up of MEPs from two European political parties, the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party and the European Democratic Party, which collectively form the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The ALDE Group traced its unofficial origin back to September 1952 and the first meeting of the Parliament's predecessor, the Common Assembly of the European Coal and Steel Community.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] Founded as an explicitly liberal group, it expanded its remit to cover the different traditions of each new Member State as they acceded to the Union, progressively changing its name in the process.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] Its immediate predecessor was the European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party Group (ELDR).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The ALDE Group was the fourth-largest group in the Eighth European Parliament term, and previously participated in an informal coalition with the EPP during the Sixth Parliament (2004–2009).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The pro-European platform of ALDE was in support of free market economics and pushed for European integration and the European single market.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] On 12 June 2019, it was announced that the successor group in alliance with La République En Marche! would be named Renew Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] In 1999, the Group partnered with European People's Party–European Democrats (EPP-ED) group to form an informal coalition for the Fifth Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] This included supporting the EPP's candidate for President of the Parliament in 1999 and the ALDE candidate in 2002.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] This meant that the Group secured its first President of the European Parliament since Simone Veil, when Pat Cox was elected to the post to serve the latter half of the Parliament's five-year term.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] This arrangement was discontinued after the 2009 election, when the EPP and the socialist S&D Group formed an informal Grand Coalition.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The Group accordingly became the Group of the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe (ALDE) on 20 July 2004, to match the eponymous transnational political alliance, although the two European-level parties remained separate outside the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The MEP Graham Watson of the British Liberal Democrats became the first chair of ALDE.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] In May 2019, speaking at a debate leading up to the 2019 European Parliament election, ALDE President Guy Verhofstadt announced that following the election, the group would form a new, centrist alliance with Emmanuel Macron's "Renaissance" list and be renamed as Renew Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The Democratic Party left the ALDE for S&D in 2009.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] Jens Rhode was originally also elected for Ventre, but left to join Danish Social Liberal Party in December 2015.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] Fianna Fáil was then a member of Union for Europe of the Nations.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The sole Fianna Fáil member sat with the European Conservatives and Reformists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] Following the 2014 European Parliament election, the National Liberal Party (PNL) left ALDE to join the European People's Party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] Reelected MEPs Norica Nicolai and Renate Weber rejoined the ALDE group later and were subsequently expelled from their party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] In September 1952, the third-largest grouping in the Common Assembly was the Liberal grouping with 11 members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The Group of Liberals and Allies was officially founded on 23 June 1953.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] By mid-September 1953, it was again the third-largest Group with 10 members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] ALDE was a coalition of liberal and centrist MEPs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] It did not have formal subgroups, although the MEPs fell naturally into two informal subgroups, depending on whether they associated with the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party or the European Democratic Party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The Bureau was the main decision making body of the ALDE Group and is composed of the leaders of the delegations from each member state that elects ALDE MEPs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The Bureau oversaw the ALDE Group's main strategy and policies and was headed by a chair (referred to as the *Leader*).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] The day-to-day running of the Group was performed by its secretariat, led by its Secretary-General.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] Along with the other political groups, ALDE has been analysed by academics on its positions regarding various issues.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-european-parliament-group] In short, it's a group of cohesive, gender-balanced centrist Euroneutrals that cooperate most closely with the EPP, are ambiguous on hypothetical EU taxes and supportive of eventual full Turkish accession to the European Union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The Mission of the ALDE-PACE group is to promote core values of the Council of Europe: democracy, human rights and the rule of law through enhanced political actions inside and outside the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] ALDE adopted a new mission statement 22 January 2018 outlining the values and objectives of the group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] ALDE members realize these objectives by actively participating in the Parliamentary Assembly sessions, working in its Committees, drafting reports, initiating debates and ensuring the follow-up of this work in their home countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Outside the Assembly the group members are committed to promoting the principles of the Council of Europe and giving support to liberal and democratic values throughout Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] According to the Rules of Procedure of the ALDE-PACE (as amended on 22 January 2018), the Bureau of the Group consists of the Chairperson, 11 Vice-Chairpersons and the Treasurer of the Group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Chairpersons of committees and former Chairpersons of the Group are ex officio members of the Bureau.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The permanent secretariat of the Group is located in the headquarters of the Council of Europe in Strasbourg, France (Palais de l’Europe).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The secretariat is chaired by Dr Maria Bigday.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] It was not until after the celebration of the Council of Europe's 25th anniversary in 1964 that the Rules of Procedure of the Consultative Assembly (its name was not changed to Parliamentary Assembly until 1974) discreetly mentioned that members had the possibility of forming political groups.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The history of the liberal group in the PACE dates back to the early 1970s (first documented in 1974).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] At the time it was called the Liberal Group and consisted of 30 members headed by Frederik Portheine (Netherlands).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] In the mid-80s the group changed its name to the "Liberal, Democratic and Reformers' Group" (LDR) in order to make the Group's political ideals universally and unequivocally recognisable.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The name "Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe" (ALDE) was adopted on 20 June 2005 in order to enhance cooperation with other European liberal and democratic bodies, in particular the ALDE of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Daniel Tarschys (Sweden) was Secretary General of the Council of Europe from 1994 - 1999.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The permanent secretariat of the Group operates since 1978, when Mr Peter Kallenberger was appointed Secretary of the Group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] After he retired in 2010, Ms Maria Bigday took up the position of the Secretary.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The ALDE-PACE Group regularly holds conferences, hearings, seminars and round tables in the framework of the Council of Europe scope of interest.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] It also co-organises joint events with other European and international liberal and democratic institutions.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Information relating to these side events is found on the ALDE-PACE Pace website and in the ALDE newsletter published after each session.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The ALDE-PACE holds stable partnership with major European and world liberal and democratic organisations.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The **Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party** (**ALDE Party**) is a liberal European political party composed of national parties from across Europe, mainly active in the European Union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The ALDE Party is affiliated with Liberal International and a recognised European political party, incorporated as a non-profit association under Belgian law.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] It was founded on 26 March 1976 in Stuttgart as a confederation of national political parties under the name "Federation of Liberal and Democrat Parties in Europe" and renamed "European Liberals and Democrats" (ELD) in 1977 and "European Liberal Democrats and Reformists" (ELDR) in 1986.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 30 April 2004, the ELDR was reformed as an official European party, the "European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party" (ELDR Party).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Prior to the 2004 European election, the European party had been represented through its own group, the European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party Group (ELDR) Group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In June 2019, the ALDE group was succeeded by Renew Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of 2024, ALDE Party is represented in European Union institutions, with 51 MEPs and five members of the European Commission.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Of the 27 EU member states, there are two with ALDE-affiliated Prime Ministers: Kristen Michal (Estonian Reform Party) in Estonia and Alexander De Croo (Open VLD) in Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE Party members are also in governments in ten other EU member states: Cyprus, France, Denmark, Finland, Sweden, Ireland, Luxembourg, Lithuania, Germany and the Netherlands.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Charles Michel, former Belgian prime minister, was the president of the European Council until December 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE's think tank is the European Liberal Forum, led by Jan-Christoph Oetjen MEP, and gathers 46 member organisations.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The youth wing of ALDE is the European Liberal Youth (LYMEC), which is predominantly based upon youth and student liberal organisations but contains also a small number of individual members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 2011, ALDE Party became the first pan-European party to create the status of individual membership.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Since then, between 1000 and close to 3000 members (the numbers fluctuate annually) maintained direct membership in the ALDE Party from several EU countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Over 40 coordinators mobilised liberal ideas, initiatives and expertise across the continent under the leadership of the steering committee, which was first chaired by Julie Cantalou.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The ALDE Party took a step further in the direction of becoming a truly pan-European party when granting voting rights to individual members' delegates at the Party Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Individual membership was eventually discontinued in 2023.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 2025, the Alliance was declared an undesirable organization in Russia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Pan-European liberalism has a long history dating back to the foundation of Liberal International in April 1947.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 26 March 1976, the Federation of Liberal and Democrat Parties in Europe was established in Stuttgart.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The founding parties of the federation were the Free Democratic Party of Germany, Radical Party of France, Venstre of Denmark, Italian Liberal Party, Dutch People's Party for Freedom and Democracy and Democratic Party of Luxembourg.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Observer members joining later in 1976 were the Danish Social Liberal Party, French Radical Party of the Left and Independent Republicans, British Liberal Party, and Italian Republican Party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 1977, the federation was renamed European Liberals and Democrats, in 1986, European Liberal Democrats and Reformists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 10 November 2012, the ELDR Party adopted the name of the alliance between the two parties, to match the parliamentary group and the alliance.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 12 June 2019, the ALDE group was succeeded by a new enlarged group, Renew Europe, which primarily consists of ALDE and EDP member parties and France's La République En Marche!
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As a registered European political party, ALDE is entitled to European public funding, which it has received continuously since 2004.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of European public funding received by ALDE.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In line with the Regulation on European political parties and European political foundations, ALDE also raises private funds to co-finance its activities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of 2025, European parties must raise at least 10% of their reimbursable expenditure from private sources, while the rest can be covered using European public funding.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of contributions and donations received by the ALDE.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of January 2026 ALDE party had 55 full member and ten affiliated parties from EU and non-EU countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Only delegates from full members of the ALDE Party and its youth wing LYMEC, together with the delegates of the ALDE Party Supporters and ALDE Party Bureau members, are permitted to vote at the ALDE Congress and Council.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Affiliated member parties have non-voting delegates.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE also includes a number of individual members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] For many years, ALDE had the largest number of individual members of all European parties; however, this membership was discontinued with only one individual member remaining as of 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As most other European parties, it has not sought to develop mass individual membership.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of individual membership of ALDE since 2019.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] Brasseur began her political career when she was elected to the city council of Luxembourg in 1976.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] She was the president of the *Association des Femmes Libérales*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] From 1999 to 2004 Brasseur was a cabinet minister of Luxembourg, Minister for National Education, Vocational Training and Sports (Ministre de l'Éducation nationale, de la Formation professionnelle et des Sports), in the government of Prime Minister Jean-Claude Juncker.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] From 2009 to 2014, Brasseur was president of The Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe in the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe (ALDE-PACE).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] In January 2014, she was elected President of the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe; she received an absolute majority of votes in the first round.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] On 26 January 2015, she was re-elected for a new mandate of one year.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] From 2016 to 2018, she had served as a member of the Committee on Legal Affairs and Human Rights; the Sub-Committee on Crime Problems and the Fight against Terrorism; and the Sub-Committee on the Middle East and the Arab World.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] Early in Brasseur's tenure as president of PACE, the assembly in April 2014 suspended the Russian delegation's voting rights after the Russian annexation of Crimea in March 2014.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] Throughout her time in office, she maintained a constant dialogue with Russian Duma Speaker Sergey Naryshkin and Russia's PACE delegates.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] Brasseur criticized Poland's judiciary reform.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] In June 2007, the Council of Europe's Committee on Culture, Science and Education released a report entitled "The Dangers of Creationism in Education." According to Brasseur, who served as co-author of the report, its goal was to firmly anchor the theory of evolution in school curricula.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] However, she was later pressured to shorten references in the resolution to "evolution by natural selection" to "evolution" because some members had misunderstood the reference to natural selection to be an attack on their religious beliefs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/anne-brasseur] The council ultimately approved the report's recommendations, with 48 votes in favor and 25 against.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium is a parliamentary constitutional monarchy with a complex federal system structured on regional and linguistic grounds.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The country is divided into three highly autonomous regions: the Flemish Region (Flanders) in the north, the Walloon Region (Wallonia) in the south, and the Brussels-Capital Region in the middle.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium's linguistic diversity and related political conflicts are reflected in its complex system of governance, made up of six different governments.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium is a developed country with an advanced high-income economy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Brussels also hosts the headquarters of many major international organizations, such as NATO.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In antiquity, present-day Belgium was dominated by the Belgae before being annexed into the Roman Empire in the mid first century BC.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] During the Middle Ages, Belgium's central location kept it relatively prosperous and connected both commercially and politically to its larger neighbours; it was part of the Carolingian Empire, the succeeding Holy Roman Empire, and subsequently the Burgundian Netherlands.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Following rule by Habsburg Spain (1556–1714), the Austrian Habsburgs (1714–1794), and Revolutionary France (1794–1815), most of modern-day Belgium was incorporated into the United Kingdom of the Netherlands after the Congress of Vienna in 1815.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Centuries of being contested and controlled by various European powers earned Belgium the moniker "the Battlefield of Europe", a reputation reinforced in the 20th century by both world wars.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] An independent Belgium was established in 1830 following the Belgian Revolution.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In the 19th century it was one of the earliest participants of the Industrial Revolution, and the first country in continental Europe to become industrialised.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] By the early 20th century, it possessed several colonies, notably the Belgian Congo and Ruanda-Urundi, which gained independence between 1960 and 1962.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The second half of the 20th century was marked by rising tensions between the Dutch-speakers and French-speakers, fueled by differences in political culture and the unequal economic development of Flanders and Wallonia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] This has resulted in several far-reaching state reforms, including the transition from a unitary to federal structure between 1970 and 1993.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Tensions persist amid ongoing reforms; the country faces a strong separatist sentiment among the Flemish, controversial language laws, and a fragmented political landscape that resulted in a record 589 days without a government formation following the 2010 federal election.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In his account of the Roman invasion of Gaul, Roman leader Julius Caesar noted that the original Belgae inhabited the northern part of Gaul extending from the Seine and Marne rivers to the Rhine.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] They therefore inhabited most of modern Belgium, and significant parts of France, the Netherlands, and Germany.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] He described the Belgae as the bravest of the Gauls, and attributed this to their distance from the Roman Province, minimal contact with merchants importing luxury goods, and their continual warfare with the neighboring Germanic tribes across the Rhine.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Within this broad region, Caesar referred to a specific area as "Belgium," which was politically dominant and located in what is now northern France.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Modern Belgium, along with neighboring regions of the Netherlands and Germany, corresponds to the territories of the northernmost Belgae tribes, including the Menapii, Nervii, the Atuatuci, and the Germani Cisrhenani.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Julius Caesar described these tribes as particularly warlike and economically undeveloped, noting their kinship with the Germanic tribes east of the Rhine.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Additionally, the area around Arlon in southern Belgium was part of the territory of the Treveri tribe, whose lands extended into present-day Luxembourg and adjacent regions of France and Germany.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Following Caesar's conquests, Gallia Belgica became the Latin name for a large Roman province encompassing most of Northern Gaul, including the lands of the Belgae and Treveri.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Subsequently, Roman Belgica was divided into two parts, and the regions closer to the lower Rhine frontier, such as the eastern part of modern Belgium, were incorporated into the frontier province of Germania Inferior.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] As the central government of the Western Roman Empire collapsed, the provinces of Belgica and Germania were inhabited by a mix of Romanized populations and Germanic-speaking Franks, who came to dominate the military and political spheres.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] During the 5th century, the area came under the rule of the Frankish Merovingian kings, who initially established a kingdom ruling over the Romanized population in what is now northern France, and then conquered the other Frankish kingdoms.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] During the 8th century, the empire of the Franks came to be ruled by the Carolingian dynasty, whose centre of power included the area which is now eastern Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Over the centuries, it was divided up in many ways, but the Treaty of Verdun in 843 divided the Carolingian Empire into three kingdoms whose borders had a lasting impact on medieval political boundaries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Most of modern Belgium was in the Middle Kingdom, later known as Lotharingia, but the coastal county of Flanders, west of the Scheldt, became the northernmost part of West Francia, the predecessor of France.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 870 in the Treaty of Meerssen, modern Belgium lands all became part of the western kingdom for a period, but in 880 in the Treaty of Ribemont, Lotharingia came under the lasting control of the eastern kingdom, which eventually became the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The lordships and bishoprics along the "March" (frontier) between the two great kingdoms maintained important connections between each other.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] For example, the county of Flanders expanded over the Scheldt into the empire, and during several periods was ruled by the same lords as the county of Hainaut.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In the 13th and 14th centuries, the cloth industry and commerce boomed especially in the County of Flanders and it became one of the richest areas in Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] This prosperity played a role in conflicts between Flanders and the king of France.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Famously, Flemish militias scored a surprise victory at the Battle of the Golden Spurs against a strong force of mounted knights in 1302, but France soon regained control of the rebellious province.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In the 15th century, the French Duchy of Burgundy took control of Flanders, and from there proceeded to unite much of present-day Benelux, the so-called Burgundian Netherlands.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] "Burgundy" and "Flanders" were the first two common names used for the Burgundian Netherlands which was the predecessor of the Austrian Netherlands, the predecessor of modern Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The union, technically stretching between two kingdoms, gave the area economic and political stability which led to an even greater prosperity and artistic creation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Born in Belgium, the Habsburg Emperor Charles V was heir of the Burgundians, but also of the royal families of Austria, Castile and Aragon.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] With the Pragmatic Sanction of 1549 he gave the Seventeen Provinces more legitimacy as a stable entity, rather than just a temporary personal union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] He also increased the influence of these Netherlands over the Prince-Bishopric of Liège, which continued to exist as a large semi-independent enclave.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Eighty Years' War (1568–1648) was triggered by the Spanish government's policy towards Protestantism, which was becoming popular in the Low Countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The rebellious northern United Provinces (*Belgica Foederata* in Latin, the "Federated Netherlands") eventually separated from the Southern Netherlands (*Belgica Regia*, the "Royal Netherlands").
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The southern part continued to be ruled successively by the Spanish (Spanish Netherlands) and the Austrian House of Habsburgs (Austrian Netherlands) and comprised most of modern Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Following the campaigns of 1794 in the French Revolutionary Wars, the Low Countries – including territories that were never nominally under Habsburg rule, such as the Prince-Bishopric of Liège – were annexed by the French First Republic, ending Austrian rule in the region.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] After the dissolution of the First French Empire and the abdication of Napoleon following his defeat on the battlefield of Waterloo, the Congress of Vienna in 1814–15 created the United Kingdom of the Netherlands.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] This buffer state, located between the major European powers, united the former territories of the Dutch Republic, the Austrian Netherlands and the Prince-Bishopric of Liège, under King William I of Orange.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 1830, the Belgian Revolution led to the re-separation of the Southern Provinces from the Netherlands and to the establishment of a Catholic and bourgeois, officially French-speaking and neutral, independent Belgium under a provisional government and a national congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Since the installation of Leopold I as king on 21 July 1831, now celebrated as Belgium's National Day, Belgium has been a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy, with a *laicist* constitution based on the Napoleonic Code.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Although the franchise was initially restricted, universal suffrage for men was introduced after the general strike of 1893 (with plural voting until 1919) and for women in 1949.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The main political parties of the 19th century were the Catholic Party and the Liberal Party, with the Belgian Labour Party emerging towards the end of the 19th century.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] French was originally the official language used by the nobility and the bourgeoisie, particularly after the rejection of the Dutch monarchy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] French progressively lost its dominance as Dutch began to recover its status.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] This recognition became official in 1898, and in 1967, the parliament accepted a Dutch version of the Constitution.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Berlin Conference of 1885 ceded control of the Congo Free State to King Leopold II as his private possession.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] From around 1900 there was growing international concern for the extreme and savage treatment of the Congolese population under Leopold II, for whom the Congo was primarily a source of revenue from ivory and rubber production.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Many Congolese were killed by Leopold's agents for failing to meet production quotas for ivory and rubber.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 1908, this outcry led the Belgian state to assume responsibility for the government of the colony, henceforth called the Belgian Congo.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] A Belgian commission in 1919 estimated that Congo's population was half of what it was in 1879.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Germany invaded Belgium in August 1914 as part of the Schlieffen Plan to attack France, and much of the Western Front fighting of World War I occurred in western parts of the country.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The opening months of the war were known as the Rape of Belgium due to German excesses.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium assumed control of the German colonies of Ruanda-Urundi (modern-day Rwanda and Burundi) during the war, and in 1924 the League of Nations mandated them to Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In the aftermath of the First World War, Belgium annexed the Prussian districts of Eupen and Malmedy in 1925, thereby causing the presence of a German-speaking minority.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] German forces again invaded the country in May 1940, and 40,690 Belgians, over half of them Jews, were killed during the subsequent occupation and the Holocaust.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] From September 1944 to February 1945 the Allies liberated Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] After World War II, a general strike forced King Leopold III to abdicate in 1951 in favour of his son, Prince Baudouin, since many Belgians thought he had collaborated with Germany during the war.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Belgian Congo gained independence in 1960 during the Congo Crisis; Ruanda-Urundi followed with its independence two years later.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium joined NATO as a founding member and formed the Benelux group of nations with the Netherlands and Luxembourg.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium became one of the six founding members of the European Coal and Steel Community in 1951 and of the European Atomic Energy Community and European Economic Community, established in 1957.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The latter has now become the European Union, for which Belgium hosts major administrations and institutions, including the European Commission, the Council of the European Union and the extraordinary and committee sessions of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In the 1990s, Belgium saw several large scandals notably surrounding Marc Dutroux, Andre Cools, the Dioxin Affair, Agusta Scandal and the murder of Karel van Noppen.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium shares borders with France (620 km; 390 mi), Germany (162/167 km), Luxembourg (148 km; 92 mi), and the Netherlands (450 km; 280 mi).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Its total surface, including water area, is 30,689 km2 (11,849 sq mi).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] However, when the country's statistics were measured in 2018, a new calculation method was used.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Unlike previous calculations, this one included the area from the coast to the low-water line, revealing the country to be 160 km2 (62 sq mi) larger in surface area than previously thought.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium has three main geographical regions; the coastal plain in the northwest and the central plateau both belong to the Anglo-Belgian Basin, and the Ardennes uplands in the southeast to the Hercynian orogenic belt.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Paris Basin reaches a small fourth area at Belgium's southernmost tip, Belgian Lorraine.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The coastal plain consists mainly of sand dunes and polders.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Further inland lies a smooth, slowly rising landscape irrigated by numerous waterways, with fertile valleys and the northeastern sandy plain of the Campine (*Kempen*).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The thickly forested hills and plateaus of the Ardennes are more rugged and rocky with caves and small gorges.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Extending westward into France, this area is eastwardly connected to the Eifel in Germany by the High Fens plateau, on which the Signal de Botrange forms the country's highest point at 694 m (2,277 ft).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The climate is maritime temperate with significant precipitation in all seasons (Köppen climate classification: *Cfb*), like most of northwest Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The average temperature is lowest in January at 3 °C (37.4 °F) and highest in July at 18 °C (64.4 °F).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The average precipitation per month varies between 54 mm (2.1 in) for February and April, to 78 mm (3.1 in) for July.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Averages for the years 2000 to 2006 show daily temperature minimums of 7 °C (44.6 °F) and maximums of 14 °C (57.2 °F) and monthly rainfall of 74 mm (2.9 in); these are about 1 °C and nearly 10 millimeters above last century's normal values, respectively.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Climate change in Belgium has caused temperatures rises and more frequent and intense heatwaves, increases in winter rainfall and decreases in snowfall.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] By 2100, sea levels along the Belgian coast are projected to rise by 60 to 90 cm with a maximum potential increase of up to 200 cm in the worst-case scenario.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The costs of climate change are estimated to amount to €9.5 billion a year in 2050 (2% of Belgian GDP), mainly due to extreme heat, drought and flooding, while economics gains due to milder winters amount to approximately €3 billion a year (0.65% of GDP).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 2023, Belgium emitted 106.82 million tonnes of greenhouse gases (around 0.2% of the global total emissions), equivalent to 9.12 tonnes per person.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The country has committed to net zero by 2050.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Phytogeographically, Belgium is shared between the Atlantic European and Central European provinces of the Circumboreal Region within the Boreal Kingdom.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] According to the World Wide Fund for Nature, the territory of Belgium belongs to the terrestrial ecoregions of Atlantic mixed forests and Western European broadleaf forests.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 1.36/10, ranking it 163rd globally out of 172 countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In Belgium forest cover is around 23% of the total land area, equivalent to 689,300 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, up from 677,400 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 251,200 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 438,200 hectares (ha).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] For the year 2015, 47% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 53% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The territory of Belgium is divided into three Regions, two of which, the Flemish Region and Walloon Region, are in turn subdivided into provinces; the third Region, the Brussels-Capital Region, is neither a province nor a part of a province.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium is a constitutional, popular monarchy and a federal parliamentary democracy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The bicameral federal parliament is composed of a Senate and a Chamber of Representatives.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The former is made up of 50 senators appointed by the parliaments of the communities and regions and 10 co-opted senators.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Prior to 2014, most of the Senate's members were directly elected.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Chamber's 150 representatives are elected under a proportional voting system from 11 electoral districts.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium has compulsory voting and thus maintains one of the highest rates of voter turnout in the world.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The King (currently Philippe) is the head of state, though with limited prerogatives.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] He appoints ministers, including a Prime Minister, that have the confidence of the Chamber of Representatives to form the federal government.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Council of Ministers is composed of no more than fifteen members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] With the possible exception of the Prime Minister, the Council of Ministers is composed of an equal number of Dutch-speaking members and French-speaking members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The judicial system is based on civil law and originates from the Napoleonic Code.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Court of Cassation is the court of last resort, with the courts of appeal one level below.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium's political institutions are complex; most political power rests on representation of the main cultural communities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Since about 1970, the significant national Belgian political parties have split into distinct components that mainly represent the political and linguistic interests of these communities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The major parties in each community, though close to the political center, belong to three main groups: Christian Democrats, Liberals, and Social Democrats.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Further notable parties came into being well after the middle of last century, mainly to represent linguistic, nationalist, or environmental interests, and recently smaller ones of some specific liberal nature.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] A string of Christian Democrat coalition governments from 1958 was broken in 1999 after the first dioxin crisis, a major food contamination scandal.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] A "rainbow coalition" emerged from six parties: the Flemish and the French-speaking Liberals, Social Democrats and Greens.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Later, a "purple coalition" of Liberals and Social Democrats formed after the Greens lost most of their seats in the 2003 election.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The government led by Prime Minister Guy Verhofstadt from 1999 to 2007 achieved a balanced budget, some tax reforms, a labor-market reform, scheduled nuclear phase-out and instigated legislation allowing more stringent war crime and more lenient soft drug usage prosecution.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Restrictions on euthanasia were reduced.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 2003, Belgium became one of the first countries in the world to legalise same-sex marriage.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The government promoted active diplomacy in Africa and opposed the invasion of Iraq.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] It is the only country that does not have age restrictions on euthanasia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Verhofstadt's coalition fared badly in the June 2007 elections.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] For more than a year, the country experienced a political crisis.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] This crisis was such that many observers speculated on a possible partition of Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] From 21 December 2007 until 20 March 2008 the temporary Verhofstadt III Government was in office.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] This was a coalition of the Flemish and Francophone Christian Democrats, the Flemish and Francophone Liberals together with the Francophone Social Democrats.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] On that day, a new government, led by Flemish Christian Democrat Yves Leterme, the actual winner of the federal elections of June 2007, was sworn in by the King.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] On 15 July 2008 Leterme offered the resignation of the cabinet to the King, as no progress in constitutional reforms had been made.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In December 2008, Leterme once more offered his resignation after a crisis surrounding the sale of Fortis to BNP Paribas.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] At this juncture, his resignation was accepted and Christian Democratic and Flemish Herman Van Rompuy was sworn in as Prime Minister on 30 December 2008.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] After Herman Van Rompuy was designated the first permanent President of the European Council on 19 November 2009, he offered the resignation of his government to King Albert II on 25 November 2009.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] A few hours later, the new government under Prime Minister Yves Leterme was sworn in.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] On 22 April 2010, Leterme again offered the resignation of his cabinet to the King after one of the coalition partners, the OpenVLD, withdrew from the government, and on 26 April 2010 King Albert officially accepted the resignation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Parliamentary elections in Belgium on 13 June 2010 saw the Flemish nationalist N-VA become the largest party in Flanders, and the Socialist Party PS the largest party in Wallonia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Until December 2011, Belgium was governed by Leterme's caretaker government awaiting the end of the deadlocked negotiations for formation of a new government.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] By 30 March 2011, this set a new world record for the elapsed time without an official government, previously held by war-torn Iraq.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Finally, in December 2011 the Di Rupo Government led by Walloon socialist Prime Minister Elio Di Rupo was sworn in.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The 2014 federal election (coinciding with the regional elections) resulted in a further electoral gain for the Flemish nationalist N-VA.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] However, the incumbent coalition (composed of Flemish and French-speaking Social Democrats, Liberals, and Christian Democrats) maintained a solid majority in Parliament and all electoral constituencies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] On 22 July 2014, King Philippe nominated Charles Michel (MR) and Kris Peeters (CD&V) to lead the formation of a new federal cabinet composed of the Flemish parties N-VA, CD&V, Open Vld and the French-speaking MR, which resulted in the Michel Government.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] It was the first time N-VA was part of the federal cabinet, while the French-speaking side was represented only by the MR, which achieved a minority of the public votes in Wallonia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In May 2019 federal elections in the Flemish-speaking northern region of Flanders, the far-right Vlaams Belang party made major gains.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In the French-speaking southern area of Wallonia, the Socialists were strong.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The moderate Flemish nationalist party, the N-VA, remained the largest party in parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In July 2019, Prime Minister Charles Michel was selected to hold the post of President of the European Council.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] His successor Sophie Wilmès was Belgium's first female prime minister.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] She led the caretaker government since October 2019.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Flemish Liberal party politician Alexander De Croo became the new prime minister in October 2020.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The parties had agreed on the federal government 16 months after the elections.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] On 3 February 2025, Bart De Wever, leader of the New Flemish Alliance, became the new prime minister.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] He is the first Flemish nationalist to be named Belgian premier.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Following a usage which can be traced back to the Burgundian and Habsburg courts, in the 19th century it was necessary to speak French to belong to the governing upper class, and those who could only speak Dutch were effectively second-class citizens.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Late that century, and continuing into the 20th century, Flemish movements evolved to counter this situation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] While the people in Southern Belgium spoke French or dialects of French, and most Brusselers adopted French as their first language, the Flemings refused to do so and succeeded progressively in making Dutch an equal language in the education system.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Following World War II, Belgian politics became increasingly dominated by the autonomy of its two main linguistic communities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Intercommunal tensions rose and the constitution was amended to minimize the potential for conflict.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The constitutional language areas determine the official languages in their municipalities, as well as the geographical limits of the empowered institutions for specific matters.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Although this would allow for seven parliaments and governments when the Communities and Regions were created in 1980, Flemish politicians decided to merge both.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Thus the Flemings just have one single institutional body of parliament and government is empowered for all except federal and specific municipal matters.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Conflicts about jurisdiction between the bodies are resolved by the Constitutional Court of Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The structure is intended as a compromise to allow different cultures to live together peacefully.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Federal State's authority includes justice, defense, federal police, social security, nuclear energy, monetary policy and public debt, and other aspects of public finances.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] State-owned companies include the Belgian Post Group and Belgian Railways.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Federal Government is responsible for the obligations of Belgium and its federalized institutions towards the European Union and NATO.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] It controls substantial parts of public health, home affairs and foreign affairs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The budget—without the debt—controlled by the federal government amounts to about 50% of the national fiscal income.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The federal government employs around 12% of the civil servants.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Communities exercise their authority only within linguistically determined geographical boundaries, originally oriented towards the individuals of a Community's language: culture (including audiovisual media), education and the use of the relevant language.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Extensions to personal matters less directly connected with language comprise health policy (curative and preventive medicine) and assistance to individuals (protection of youth, social welfare, aid to families, immigrant assistance services, and so on.).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Regions have authority in fields that can be broadly associated with their territory.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] These include economy, employment, agriculture, water policy, housing, public works, energy, transport, the environment, town and country planning, nature conservation, credit and foreign trade.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] They supervise the provinces, municipalities and intercommunal utility companies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In several fields, the different levels each have their own say on specifics.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] With education, for instance, the autonomy of the Communities neither includes decisions about the compulsory aspect nor allows for setting minimum requirements for awarding qualifications, which remain federal matters.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Each level of government can be involved in scientific research and international relations associated with its powers.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The treaty-making power of the Regions' and Communities' Governments is the broadest of all the Federating units of all the Federations all over the world.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Because of its location at the crossroads of Western Europe, Belgium has historically been the route of invading armies from its larger neighbors.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] With virtually defenseless borders, Belgium has traditionally sought to avoid domination by the more powerful nations which surround it through a policy of mediation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Belgians have been strong advocates of European integration.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The headquarters of NATO and of several of the institutions of the European Union are located in Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Belgian Armed Forces had 23,200 active personnel in 2023, including 8,500 in the Land Component, 1,400 in the Naval Component, 4,900 in the Air Component, 1,450 in the Medical Component, and 6,950 in joint service, in addition to 5,900 reserve personnel.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 2019, Belgium's defense budget totaled €4.303 billion ($4.921 billion) representing .93% of its GDP.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The operational commands of the four components are subordinate to the Staff Department for Operations and Training of the Ministry of Defense, which is headed by the Assistant Chief of Staff Operations and Training, and to the Chief of Defense.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Belgian military consists of volunteers (conscription was abolished in 1995), and citizens of other EU states, Iceland, Norway, Switzerland, or Lichtenstein are also able to join.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium has troops deployed in several African countries as part of UN or EU missions, in Iraq for the war against the Islamic State, and in eastern Europe for the NATO presence there.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The effects of the Second World War made collective security a priority for Belgian foreign policy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In March 1948 Belgium signed the Treaty of Brussels and then joined NATO in 1948.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] However, the integration of the armed forces into NATO did not begin until after the Korean War.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Belgians, along with the Luxembourg government, sent a detachment of battalion strength to fight in Korea known as the Belgian United Nations Command.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] This mission was the first in a long line of UN missions which the Belgians supported.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Currently, the Belgian Marine Component is working closely together with the Dutch Navy under the command of the Admiral Benelux.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] According to the 2024 Global Peace Index, Belgium is the 16th most peaceful country in the world.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium's strongly globalized economy and its transport infrastructure are integrated with the rest of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Its location at the heart of a highly industrialized region helped make it the world's 15th largest trading nation in 2007.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The economy is characterized by a highly productive work force, high GNP and high exports per capita.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium's main imports are raw materials, machinery and equipment, chemicals, raw diamonds, pharmaceuticals, foodstuffs, transportation equipment, and oil products.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Its main exports are machinery and equipment, chemicals, finished diamonds, metals and metal products, and foodstuffs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The Belgian economy is heavily service-oriented and shows a dual nature: a dynamic Flemish economy and a Walloon economy that lags behind.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] One of the founding members of the European Union, Belgium strongly supports an open economy and the extension of the powers of EU institutions to integrate member economies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Since 1922, through the Belgium-Luxembourg Economic Union, Belgium and Luxembourg have been a single trade market with customs and currency union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium was the first continental European country to undergo the Industrial Revolution, in the early 19th century.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Areas in Liège Province and around Charleroi rapidly developed mining and steelmaking, which flourished until the mid-20th century in the Sambre and Meuse valley and made Belgium one of the three most industrialized nations in the world from 1830 to 1910.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] However, by the 1840s the textile industry of Flanders was in severe crisis, and the region experienced famine from 1846 to 1850.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] After World War II, Ghent and Antwerp experienced a rapid expansion of the chemical and petroleum industries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The 1973 and 1979 oil crises sent the economy into a recession; it was particularly prolonged in Wallonia, where the steel industry had become less competitive and experienced a serious decline.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In the 1980s and 1990s, the economic center of the country continued to shift northwards and is now concentrated in the populous Flemish Diamond area.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] By the end of the 1980s, Belgian macroeconomic policies had resulted in a cumulative government debt of about 120% of GDP.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] As of 2006, the budget was balanced and public debt was equal to 90.30% of GDP.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 2005 and 2006, real GDP growth rates of 1.5% and 3.0%, respectively, were slightly above the average for the Euro area.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Unemployment rates of 8.4% in 2005 and 8.2% in 2006 were close to the area average.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] By October 2010, this had grown to 8.5% compared to an average rate of 9.6% for the European Union as a whole (EU 27).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] From 1832 until 2002, Belgium's currency was the Belgian franc.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium switched to the euro in 2002, with the first sets of euro coins being minted in 1999.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The standard Belgian euro coins designated for circulation show the portrait of the monarch (first King Albert II, since 2013 King Philippe).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Despite an 18% decrease observed from 1970 to 1999, Belgium still had in 1999 the highest rail network density within the European Union with 113.8 km/1 000 km2.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] On the other hand, the same period, 1970–1999, has seen a huge growth (+56%) of the motorway network.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 1999, the density of km motorways per 1000 km2 and 1000 inhabitants amounted to 55.1 and 16.5 respectively and were significantly superior to the EU's means of 13.7 and 15.9.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] From a biological resource perspective, Belgium has a low endowment: Belgium's biocapacity adds up to only 0.8 global hectares in 2016, just about half of the 1.6 global hectares of biocapacity available per person worldwide.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In contrast, in 2016, Belgians used on average 6.3 global hectares of biocapacity - their ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] This means they required about eight times as much biocapacity as Belgium contains.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] As a result, Belgium was running a biocapacity deficit of 5.5 global hectares per person in 2016.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Belgium experiences some of the most congested traffic in Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 2010, commuters to the cities of Brussels and Antwerp spent respectively 65 and 64 hours a year in traffic jams.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Like in most small European countries, more than 80% of the airways traffic is handled by a single airport, the Brussels Airport.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The ports of Antwerp and Zeebrugge (Bruges) share more than 80% of Belgian maritime traffic, Antwerp being the second European harbor with a gross weight of goods handled of 115 988 000 t in 2000 after a growth of 10.9% over the preceding five years.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 2016, the port of Antwerp handled 214 million tons after a year-on-year growth of 2.7%.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] There is a large economic gap between Flanders and Wallonia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Wallonia was historically wealthy compared to Flanders, mostly due to its heavy industries, but the decline of the steel industry post-World War II led to the region's rapid decline, whereas Flanders rose swiftly.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Since then, Flanders has been prosperous, among the wealthiest regions in Europe, whereas Wallonia has been languishing.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] As of 2007, the unemployment rate of Wallonia is over double that of Flanders.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The divide has played a key part in the tensions between the Flemish and Walloons in addition to the already-existing language divide.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Pro-independence movements have gained high popularity in Flanders as a consequence.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The separatist New Flemish Alliance (N-VA) party, for instance, is the largest party in Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Contributions to the development of science and technology have appeared throughout the country's history.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] The 16th century Early Modern flourishing of Western Europe included cartographer Gerardus Mercator, anatomist Andreas Vesalius, herbalist Rembert Dodoens and mathematician Simon Stevin among the most influential scientists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Chemist Ernest Solvay and engineer Zenobe Gramme (École industrielle de Liège) gave their names to the Solvay process and the Gramme dynamo, respectively, in the 1860s.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Bakelite was developed in 1907–1909 by Leo Baekeland.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Ernest Solvay also acted as a major philanthropist and gave his name to the Solvay Institute of Sociology, the Solvay Brussels School of Economics and Management and the International Solvay Institutes for Physics and Chemistry which are now part of the Université libre de Bruxelles.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] In 1911, he started a series of conferences, the Solvay Conferences on Physics and Chemistry, which have had a deep impact on the evolution of quantum physics and chemistry.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] A major contribution to fundamental science was also due to a Belgian, Monsignor Georges Lemaître (Catholic University of Louvain), who is credited with proposing the Big Bang theory of the origin of the universe in 1927.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Three Nobel Prizes in Physiology or Medicine were awarded to Belgians: Jules Bordet (Université libre de Bruxelles) in 1919, Corneille Heymans (University of Ghent) in 1938 and Albert Claude (Université libre de Bruxelles) together with Christian de Duve (Université catholique de Louvain) in 1974.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] François Englert (Université libre de Bruxelles) was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2013.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Ilya Prigogine (Université libre de Bruxelles) was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1977.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p01] Two Belgian mathematicians have been awarded the Fields Medal: Pierre Deligne in 1978 and Jean Bourgain in 1994.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] As of 1 January 2024, the total population of Belgium according to its population register was 11,763,650.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The population density of Belgium is 383/km2 (990/sq mi) as of January 2024, making it the 22nd most densely populated country in the world, and the 6th most densely populated country in Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The most densely populated province is Antwerp, the least densely populated province is Luxembourg.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The Brussels-Capital Region (Brussels) had a population of 1,249,597 (10.6% of Belgium), consisting of 19 municipalities, its most populous cities being the City of Brussels (197,000), Schaerbeek (130,000), and Anderlecht (127,000).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] In 2023 the average total fertility rate (TFR) across Belgium was 1.38 children per woman, below the replacement rate of 2.1; it remains considerably below the high of 4.87 children born per woman in 1873.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgium subsequently has one of the oldest populations in the world, with an average age of 41.6 years.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] As of 2007, nearly 92% of the population had Belgian citizenship, and other European Union member citizens account for around 6%.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] In 2007, there were 1.38 million foreign-born residents in Belgium, corresponding to 12.9% of the total population.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Of these, 685,000 (6.4%) were born outside the EU, and 695,000 (6.5%) were born in another EU Member State.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] At the beginning of 2012, people of foreign background and their descendants were estimated to have formed around 25% of the total population i.e.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Of these new Belgians, 1,200,000 are of European ancestry and 1,350,000 are from non-Western countries (most of them from Morocco, Turkey, and the DR Congo).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Since the modification of the Belgian nationality law in 1984, more than 1.3 million migrants have acquired Belgian citizenship.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The largest group of immigrants and their descendants in Belgium are Italian Belgians and Moroccan Belgians.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] 89.2% of inhabitants of Turkish origin have been naturalized, as have 88.4% of people of Moroccan background, 75.4% of Italians, 56.2% of the French and 47.8% of Dutch people.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Statbel released figures of the Belgian population in relation to the origin of people in Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] According to the data, as of 1 January 2021, 67.3% of the Belgian population was of ethnic Belgian origin, and 32.7% were of foreign origin or nationality, with 20.3% of those of a foreign nationality or ethnic group originating from neighbouring countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The study also found that 74.5% of the Brussels-Capital Region were of non-Belgian origin, of which 13.8% originated from neighbouring countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgium has three official languages: Dutch, French and German.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] A number of non-official minority languages are spoken as well.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] As no census exists, there are no official statistical data regarding the distribution or usage of Belgium's three official languages or their dialects.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] However, various criteria, including the language(s) of parents, of education, or the second-language status of foreign born, may provide suggested figures.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] An estimated 60% of the Belgian population are native speakers of Dutch (often referred to as Flemish), and 40% of the population speaks French natively.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] French-speaking Belgians are often referred to as Walloons, although the French speakers in Brussels are not Walloons.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The total number of native Dutch speakers is estimated to be about 6.23 million, concentrated in the northern Flanders region, while native French speakers number 3.32 million in Wallonia and an estimated 870,000 (or 85%) in the officially bilingual Brussels-Capital Region.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The German-speaking Community is made up of 73,000 people in the east of the Walloon Region; around 10,000 German and 60,000 Belgian nationals are speakers of German.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Roughly 23,000 more German speakers live in municipalities near the official Community.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Both Belgian Dutch and Belgian French have minor differences in vocabulary and semantic nuances from the varieties spoken respectively in the Netherlands and France.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Many Flemish people still speak dialects of Dutch in their local environment.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Walloon, considered either as a dialect of French or a distinct Romance language, is now only understood and spoken occasionally, mostly by elderly people.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Walloon is divided into four dialects, which along with those of Picard, are rarely used in public life and have largely been replaced by French.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The Constitution of Belgium provides for freedom of religion, and the government respects this right in practice.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgium officially recognizes three religions: Christianity (Catholic, Protestantism, Orthodox churches and Anglicanism), Islam and Judaism.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] During the reigns of Albert I and Baudouin, the Belgian royal family had a reputation of deeply rooted Catholicism.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Catholicism has traditionally been Belgium's majority religion; being especially strong in Flanders.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] However, by 2009 Sunday church attendance was 5% for Belgium in total; 3% in Brussels, and 5.4% in Flanders.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Church attendance in 2009 in Belgium was roughly half of the Sunday church attendance in 1998 (11% for the total of Belgium in 1998).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Despite the drop in church attendance, Catholic identity nevertheless remains an important part of Belgium's culture.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The European Social Survey in 2023 found that people who did not belong to a religion comprised 59% of the population.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The share of Christians was 34%, with Catholicism being the largest denomination at 31% of the population.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Protestants and other Christians comprised 2% and Orthodox Christians comprised 1%.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Islam is the second largest religion with 6% of the population.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] According to the Eurobarometer 2010, 37% of Belgian citizens believe in God, 31% in some sort of spirit or life-force.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] 27% do not believe in any sort of spirit, God, or life-force.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] According to the Eurobarometer 2021, 49% of the total population of Belgium adhered to Christianity, with Catholicism being the largest denomination with 44%.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Protestants comprised 1% and Orthodox Christians were 1% of the total, other Christians were 3%.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Non-religious people comprised 41% of the population and were divided between atheists (15%) and agnostics or non-believers (26%).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] A further 2% of the population was Muslim.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] In the early 2000s, there were approximately 42,000 Jews in Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The Jewish Community of Antwerp (numbering some 18,000) is one of the largest in Europe, and one of the last places in the world where Yiddish is the primary language of a large Jewish community (mirroring certain Orthodox and Hasidic communities in New York, New Jersey, and Israel).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] In addition, most Jewish children in Antwerp receive a Jewish education.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] There are several Jewish newspapers and more than 45 active synagogues (30 of which are in Antwerp) in the country.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Sociologist Jan Hertogen estimated that in 2022 approximately 9.6% of the Belgian population was Muslim.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Muslims constituted 24.1% of the population of Brussels, 8% of Wallonia and 7.6% of Flanders.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] According to 2012 estimates, the average life expectancy is 79.65 years.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Since 1960, life expectancy has, in line with the European average, grown by two months per year.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Death in Belgium is mainly due to heart and vascular disorders, neoplasms, disorders of the respiratory system and unnatural causes of death (accidents, suicide).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Non-natural causes of death and cancer are the most common causes of death for females up to age 24 and males up to age 44.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Healthcare is financed through both social security contributions and taxation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Health care is delivered by a mixed public and private system of independent medical practitioners and public, university and semi-private hospitals.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Charges for health care services are paid by the patient and reimbursed later by health insurance institutions, but for ineligible categories (of patients and services) so-called third party payment systems exist.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The Belgian health care system is supervised and financed by the federal government, and the Flemish and Walloon regional governments, and the German Community also has (indirect) oversight and responsibilities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Despite earlier political opposition, age restrictions were lifted in 2014, allowing children and young people under the age of 18 who understood the meaning of euthanasia to request it and for euthanasia to be carried out with the consent of their parents or guardians.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] A child of unknown age with an incurable disease died through euthanasia in 2016.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Excluding assisted suicide, Belgium has the highest suicide rate in Western Europe and one of the highest suicide rates in the developed world (exceeded only by Lithuania, South Korea, and Latvia).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Education is compulsory from 6 to 18 years of age for Belgians.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Among OECD countries in 2002, Belgium had the third highest proportion of 18- to 21-year-olds enrolled in postsecondary education, at 42%.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Though an estimated 99% of the adult population is literate, concern is rising over functional illiteracy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The Programme for International Student Assessment (PISA), coordinated by the OECD, currently ranks Belgium's education as the 19th best in the world, being significantly higher than the OECD average.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Education is organized separately by each community.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The Flemish Community scores noticeably above the French and German-speaking Communities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Mirroring the structure of the 19th-century Belgian political landscape, characterized by the Liberal and the Catholic parties, the educational system is segregated into secular and religious schools.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The secular branch of schooling is controlled by the communities, the provinces, or the municipalities, while religious, mainly Catholic branch education, is organized by religious authorities, which are also subsidized and supervised by the communities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Despite its political and linguistic divisions, the region corresponding to today's Belgium has seen the flourishing of major artistic movements that have had tremendous influence on European art and culture.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Nowadays, to a certain extent, cultural life is concentrated within each language Community, and a variety of barriers have made a shared cultural sphere less pronounced.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Since the 1970s, there are no bilingual universities or colleges in the country except the Royal Military Academy and the Antwerp Maritime Academy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Contributions to painting and architecture have been especially rich.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The Mosan art, the Early Netherlandish, the Flemish Renaissance and Baroque painting and major examples of Romanesque, Gothic, Renaissance and Baroque architecture are milestones in the history of art.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] While the 15th century's art in the Low Countries is dominated by the religious paintings of Jan van Eyck and Rogier van der Weyden, the 16th century is characterized by a broader panel of styles such as Peter Breughel's landscape paintings and Lambert Lombard's representation of the antique.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Though the Baroque style of Peter Paul Rubens and Anthony van Dyck flourished in the early 17th century in the Southern Netherlands, it gradually declined thereafter.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] During the 19th and 20th centuries many original romantic, expressionist and surrealist Belgian painters emerged, including James Ensor and other artists belonging to the Les XX group, Constant Permeke, Paul Delvaux and René Magritte.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The avant-garde CoBrA movement appeared in the 1950s, while the sculptor Panamarenko remains a remarkable figure in contemporary art.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Multidisciplinary artists Jan Fabre, Wim Delvoye and the painter Luc Tuymans are other internationally renowned figures on the contemporary art scene.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgian contributions to architecture also continued into the 19th and 20th centuries, including the work of Victor Horta and Henry van de Velde, who were major initiators of the Art Nouveau style.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The vocal music of the Franco-Flemish School developed in the southern part of the Low Countries and was an important contribution to Renaissance culture.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] In the 19th and 20th centuries, there was an emergence of major violinists, such as Henri Vieuxtemps, Eugène Ysaÿe and Arthur Grumiaux, while Adolphe Sax invented the saxophone in 1846.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The composer César Franck was born in Liège in 1822.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Contemporary popular music in Belgium is also of repute.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Jazz musicians Django Reinhardt and Toots Thielemans and singer Jacques Brel have achieved global fame.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Nowadays, singer Stromae has been a musical revelation in Europe and beyond, having great success.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] In rock/pop music, Telex, Front 242, K's Choice, Hooverphonic, Zap Mama, Soulwax and dEUS are well known.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] In the heavy metal scene, bands like Machiavel, Channel Zero and Enthroned have a worldwide fan-base.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgium has produced several well-known authors, including the poets Emile Verhaeren, Guido Gezelle, Robert Goffin and novelists Hendrik Conscience, Stijn Streuvels, Georges Simenon, Suzanne Lilar, Hugo Claus and Amélie Nothomb.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The poet and playwright Maurice Maeterlinck won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1911.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] *The Adventures of Tintin* by Hergé is the best known of Franco-Belgian comics, but many other major authors, including Peyo (*The Smurfs*), André Franquin (*Gaston Lagaffe*), Morris (*Lucky Luke*), and Willy Vandersteen (*Suske en Wiske*) brought the Belgian cartoon strip industry a worldwide fame.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Additionally, crime author Agatha Christie created the character Hercule Poirot, a Belgian detective, who has served as a protagonist in a number of her mystery novels.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgian cinema has brought a number of mainly Flemish novels to life on-screen.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgian directors include André Delvaux, Stijn Coninx, Luc and Jean-Pierre Dardenne; well-known actors include Jean-Claude Van Damme, Jan Decleir and Marie Gillain; and successful films include *Bullhead, Man Bites Dog* and *The Alzheimer Affair*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgium is also home to a number of successful fashion designers.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Folklore plays a major role in Belgium's cultural life; the country has a comparatively high number of processions, cavalcades, parades, ommegangs, ducasses, kermesses, and other local festivals, nearly always with an originally religious or mythological background.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The three-day Carnival of Binche, near Mons, with its Gilles (men dressed in high, plumed hats and bright costumes) is held just before Lent (the 40 days between Ash Wednesday and Easter).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Together with the 'Processional Giants and Dragons' of Ath, Brussels, Dendermonde, Mechelen and Mons, it is recognized by UNESCO as a Masterpiece of the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Originated in 1832 and revived in the 1960s, the Gentse Feesten (a music and theatre festival organized in Ghent around Belgian National Day, on 21 July) have become a modern tradition.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Several of these festivals include sporting competitions, such as cycling, and many fall under the category of kermesses.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] A major non-official holiday is Saint Nicholas Day (Dutch: *Sinterklaas*, French: *la Saint-Nicolas*), a festivity for children, and in Liège, for students.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] It takes place each year on 6 December and is a sort of early Christmas.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] On the evening of 5 December, before going to bed, children put their shoes by the hearth with water or wine and a carrot for Saint Nicholas' horse or donkey.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] According to tradition, Saint Nicholas comes at night and travels down the chimney.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] He then takes the food and water or wine, leaves presents, goes back up, feeds his horse or donkey, and continues on his course.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] He also knows whether children have been good or bad.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] This holiday is especially loved by children in Belgium and the Netherlands.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Dutch immigrants imported the tradition into the United States, where Saint Nicholas is now known as Santa Claus.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgium is famous for beer, chocolate, waffles and French fries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The national dishes are steak and fries, and mussels with fries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Many highly ranked Belgian restaurants can be found in the most influential restaurant guides, such as the Michelin Guide.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] One of the many beers with the high prestige is that of the Trappist monks.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Technically, it is an ale and traditionally each abbey's beer is served in its own glass (the forms, heights and widths are different).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] There are only eleven breweries (six of them are Belgian) that are allowed to brew Trappist beer.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Brands of Belgian chocolate and pralines, like Côte d'Or, Neuhaus, Leonidas and Godiva are famous, as well as independent producers such as Burie and Del Rey in Antwerp and Mary's in Brussels.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgium produces over 1100 varieties of beer.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The Trappist beer of the Abbey of Westvleteren has repeatedly been rated the world's best beer.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The biggest brewer in the world by volume is Anheuser-Busch InBev, based in Leuven.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Since the 1970s, sports clubs and federations are organized separately within each language community.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The *Administration de l'Éducation Physique et du Sport* (ADEPS) is responsible for recognising the various French-speaking sports federations and also runs three sports centres in the Brussels-Capital Region.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Its Dutch-speaking counterpart is *Sport Vlaanderen* (formerly called BLOSO).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Association football is the most popular sport in both parts of Belgium; also very popular are cycling, tennis, swimming, judo and basketball.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The Belgium national football team has been among the best on the FIFA World Rankings ever since November 2015, when it reached the top spot for the first time.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Since the 1990s, the team has been the world's number one for the most years in history, only behind the records of Brazil and Spain.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] With players like Jean-Marie Pfaff and Jan Ceulemans they won the silver medal at Euro 1980, while a team with Eden Hazard, Kevin De Bruyne, Romelu Lukaku and Thibaut Courtois won the bronze medal at World Cup 2018.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgium hosted the Euro 1972, and co-hosted the Euro 2000 with the Netherlands.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgians hold the most Tour de France victories of any country except France.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] They also have the most victories on the UCI Road World Championships.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] With five victories in the Tour de France and numerous other cycling records, Belgian cyclist Eddy Merckx is often regarded as one of the greatest cyclists of all time.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Philippe Gilbert and Remco Evenepoel were the 2012 and 2022 world champions, respectively.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Other well-known Belgian cyclists are Tom Boonen, Wout van Aert and Lotte Kopecky.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Kim Clijsters and Justine Henin both were Player of the Year in the Women's Tennis Association as they were ranked the number one female tennis player.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The Spa-Francorchamps motor-racing circuit hosts the Formula One World Championship Belgian Grand Prix.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The Belgian driver, Jacky Ickx, won eight Grands Prix and six 24 Hours of Le Mans and finished twice as runner-up in the Formula One World Championship.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Belgium also has a strong reputation in, motocross with the riders Joël Robert, Roger De Coster, Georges Jobé, Eric Geboers and Stefan Everts, among others.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] Sporting events annually held in Belgium include the Memorial Van Damme athletics competition, the Belgian Grand Prix Formula One, and a number of classic cycle races such as the Tour of Flanders and Liège–Bastogne–Liège.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The 1920 Summer Olympics were held in Antwerp.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/belgium-p02] The 1977 European Basketball Championship was held in Liège and Ostend.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The **Congress of Local and Regional Authorities** is the pan-European political assembly representing local and regional authorities from the forty-six member states of the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress is made up of two chambers, the Chamber of Local Authorities and the Chamber of Regions, and holds its plenary sessions twice a year at the Palace of Europe in Strasbourg, where its permanent Secretariat is based.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The two Chambers have a total of 612 members, who each must hold an elective office (they may be regional or municipal councillors, mayors or presidents of regional authorities) and who represent over 130,000 authorities in the different states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] It encourages the devolution and regionalization processes, as well as the trans-frontier co-operation between cities and regions.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The present Congress of Local and Regional Authorities was established on 14 January 1994 with the Statutory Resolution 94(3) of the Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] However, the history of the Congress reflects the already fifty-year history of the development of local and regional democracy in Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress's predecessor, the Conference of Local Authorities of Europe was first established at the Council of Europe in 1957.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] It held its first session on 12 January 1957 in Strasbourg presided by the prominent French statesman Jacques Chaban-Delmas, who was President of the Conference from January 1957 to January 1960.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In 1975 the Committee of Ministers established the Conference of Local and Regional Authorities of Europe that brought together also representatives of European regions, not only local authorities, thus replacing and enhancing the Conference of Local Authorities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In 1979 it became the Standing Conference of Local and Regional Authorities of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Six years later, in 1985, the Standing Conference adopted the European Charter of Local Self-Government, recognizing the increasing role of the development of local democracy, which has become one of the most important achievements of the organization.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Charter was opened for signature in October 1985 and has since been signed by all Council of Europe member states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In 1994 the Standing Conference asked the Committee of Ministers to further enhance its statute, and the Standing Conference was transformed into the present Congress of Local and Regional Authorities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In 2005, during the Warsaw Summit, the Heads of State and Government of the member states of the Council of Europe reasserted the importance of local and regional democracy for Europe and underlined the major role of the Congress in its mission, again supporting its mandate.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In October 2010, the Congress adopted a comprehensive reform of its structures and activities meant to increase the impact of its action and make it more effective and more relevant to European citizens and their elected representatives.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In particular, the structural changes included the creation of three new committees, to replace the existing previous four: a Monitoring Committee, a Governance Committee and a Current Affairs Committee.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Moreover, a Statutory Forum was set up, the mandate of Congress members extended from two to four years, and the 30-per cent requirement for women's representation in national delegations applied also to substitute members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The role of the Bureau as the executive body of the Congress was strengthened, and the adopted texts subject to a clearer and more concrete follow-up procedure.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In the light of this reform, the Committee of Ministers adopted a revised version of the Statutory Resolution and the Charter of the Congress in January 2011.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress adopted its new Rules of Procedure in March 2012.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In October 2012 it adopted its priorities 2013–2016.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] These priorities are focused on 5 areas: monitoring of local and regional democracy, observation of local and regional elections, targeted post-monitoring and post-observation assistance, the local and regional dimension of human rights and streamlined thematic activities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] As political Assembly of local and regional elected representatives, the Congress is the voice of Europe's 130,000 regions and municipalities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] It promotes the strengthening of local and regional democracy in all Council of Europe member States.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress carries out monitoring missions of the local and regional authorities in member states and prepares reports on the situation in the State concerned.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] These reports and the draft resolutions and recommendations they contain are submitted to the plenary sessions which debate them in the presence of high representatives of the governments before adopting them.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The recommendations are then forwarded to the Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe which gives them the appropriate follow up whenever needed.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] It also observes local and regional elections.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] After an observation mission it drafts a report and a recommendation which are also submitted to the sessions for adoption.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Furthermore, it prepares thematic reports which, together with a recommendation and/or a resolution, are debated during its sessions.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] To fulfill its objectives the Congress cooperates with various partners: national associations, international associations, observers, civil society and other institutional partners such as the Committee of Regions of the European Union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The main task of the Chamber of Local Authorities is to assess the situation of local democracy and observe local elections based on the European Charter of Local Self-Government.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Chamber also handles social issues and supports the cooperation of European cities, such as intercultural dialogues, e-democracy, or multiculturalism.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] It promotes the principles of local democracy outside Europe, inter alia through Euro-Arab dialogue between cities and Euro-Mediterranean co-operation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] If necessary, the Chamber of Local Authorities can also require a member to write a report to a relevant question of his or her expertise.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Chamber of Local Authorities must examine issues that are relevant to its jurisdiction, namely substantive and current issues relating to the local dimension in Europe, and if necessary may raise a debate during a Congress session.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] A list of the members of this Chamber can be found here.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Chamber of Regions consists of representatives of authorities that act between the local and central levels of government.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The authority must have either self-governing or state-like powers.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] It must effectively be able to take full responsibility for a substantial share of matters of public concern, in the interest of its community, and it has to take into account the principle of subsidiarity.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Chamber of Regions meets twice a year during the plenary sessions of the Congress, holds debates on issues such as the regionalisation in Europe, and adopts resolutions and recommendations.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] It deals with the role of regions within the member states of the Congress, regional democracy, inter-regional cooperation and regional economy, among others.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The members of this Chamber can be found here.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] With the adoption of the revised Charter of the Congress on 19 January 2011, the former Standing Committee was replaced by the Statutory Forum.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] This Forum is composed of heads of all national delegations together with the members of the Bureau of Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Forum acts on behalf of the Congress between sessions and may be convened at any time by the President of the Congress, as he deems necessary.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In October 2010, the Congress set up three committees: the Monitoring Committee, the Governance Committee and the Current Affairs Committee.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] These Committees prepare most of the reports which are submitted to the Chambers or to the Plenary Sessions.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Monitoring Committee was established to follow the implementation of the commitment and obligations of the member states to the European Charter of Local Self-Government.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] It organises monitoring visits and drafts reports and recommendations on the situation of the local and regional democracy in the member states concerned.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] It encourages member states to evaluate the situation of local democracy, in relation to the Charter, and identifies the obstacles that prevent them from implementing it fully.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The members of this Committee can be found here.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Governance Committee is responsible for affairs relating to the Congress's statutory mandate.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] These include public finance, cross border and inter-regional co-operation and e-democracy as well as co-operation with intergovernmental bodies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The site of the Congress contains a list with the members of this Committee.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The members of this Committee can be found on the site of the Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Group of Independent Experts helps the three statutory committees to carry out their responsibilities in local and regional democracy, in regards to the European Charter.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The experts are recruited from universities and other research centers based on their expertise in law, economics, or political science and have a renewable term of four years.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress Secretariat is headed by the Secretary General, who is elected for five years by the plenary meeting of Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Secretary General is supported by the Congress Director.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Secretariat of the two chambers of Congress will be occupied by two executive secretaries, who are appointed by the Secretary General after consultation with the Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress is formed of national delegations made up of representatives of local and regional authorities of the 46 member States of the Council of Europe, who are either directly elected or are politically accountable to a directly elected assembly.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The membership of each member state's delegation ensures a balanced geographical distribution of territories, equitable representation of the various types of local and regional authorities and political forces, and equitable representation of women and men.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Each member state has the right to the same number of seats in the Congress as in the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Apart from full members, the delegations are also made of substitutes (who work in the same capacity).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] A list of the national delegations and their members can be found on the Congress site.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Two representatives of local government in Kosovo participate in the work of the Congress as observers.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The political groups within the Congress ensure an equitable representation, in terms of political, geographical and gender balance in each delegation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress Charter sets a minimum of representation of 30% for the under-represented sex for each delegation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress meets twice a year for the plenary sessions, which are held in Strasbourg.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The sessions for each Chamber are held during the plenary sessions.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Every two years, the Congress appoints a President from among the representatives, or full members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] See the Congress site for recent information on the political groups.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The core mission of the Congress of Local and Regional Authorities is the effective monitoring of the situation of local and regional democracy in member states by assessing the application of the European Charter of Local Self-Government.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Through this process of monitoring, the Congress contributes, at territorial level, to the main objectives of the Council of Europe, which are to advance democracy and human rights on the continent.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Monitoring is also part of an ongoing political dialogue with the different levels of governance in the State concerned.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] These recommendations are debated and adopted during the sessions of the Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] More information and examples of recently adopted texts in this area can be found here.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The observation of the local and regional elections is an important aspect of the tasks of the Congress, which complements the monitoring activities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The observation missions are conducted at the request of the responsible parties; the Congress sets up a delegation made of Congress members and members of the Committee of the Regions (some 10–15 people).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] At the close of the observation mission a preliminary statement by the Congress delegation is made.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Then a report that includes an analysis of the election campaign, voting day, and recommendations/improvements to be made is prepared and submitted to the session of the Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress collaborates with institutions of the Council of Europe such as the Parliamentary Assembly and the Venice Commission.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The details of the procedure are set out in Congress resolution More information on the observation of elections can be found on Congress site.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In March 2013 the Congress adopted Resolution 353(2013) on post-monitoring and post-observation of elections.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The aim is to develop the political dialogue with Member States and relevant stakeholders after a monitoring or election observation visit and to make recommendations for improvements.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The first roadmap prepared in the framework of this post-monitoring dialogue concerned the decentralisation reform undertaken by the Ukrainian authorities and was signed in May 2015.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In its Priorities 2013–2016, the Congress decided to further develop co-operation and partnerships with the overall objective to consolidate and advance territorial democracy in the Council of Europe member states and in its immediate neighbourhood and achieve concrete results in the field.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] These cooperation activities help to further ensure the implementation of the European Charter of Local Self-Government and the Congress recommendations.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress offers its expertise, in the field of local and regional democracy, based on needs, its members being a pool of practical and political experience.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress develops its projects within the chapter on Democracy in the Council of Europe Action Plans for member States.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] These projects are co-financed through voluntary contributions of member states and international partners.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress is also active in the neighbourhood policy of the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] This policy is aimed at helping neighbouring regions to improve democracy, the rule of law and human rights protection.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] As an example, priorities for co-operation in Morocco and Tunisia include local governance.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In the past the Congress has been active in strengthening local democracy and trans-border co-operation in Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] It has encouraged the creation of associations of local authorities and created several networks which have now evolved independently and which are privileged partners of the Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Examples of these Associations are the Association of Local Democracy Agencies (ALDA), the Network of Associations of Local Authorities of South-East Europe (NALAS) and the European Network of Local and Regional Training Establishments (ENTO).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The European Alliance of Cities and Regions for Roma Inclusion was set up by the Congress of Local and Regional Authorities with the support of Special Representative of the Council of Europe Secretary General for Roma Issues.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] More than 120 cities and regions from over 27 countries are participating in the Alliance.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] To enable participating cities and regions to speak with one voice by providing a platform for advocating on issues concerning Roma inclusion at local and regional level.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Alliance organises national and international seminars for its participating cities and regions in order to facilitate the exchange of know-how and good practices.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] One of the key priorities of the Alliance is the promotion of the Roma culture and raising awareness and knowledge about the Roma Genocide during World War II and the international commemoration day on the 2nd of August.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Another important initiative of the Council of Europe, aimed at fighting antigypsyism, is the Dosta!
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Campaign, run on a national level in the member states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] As of 2013, the Alliance is in charge of administrating the Dosta!
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Congress Prize, awarded biannually to three municipalities for their successful and innovative projects in the field of Roma inclusion.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] In 2013–2014 the Alliance implemented the first stage of the project named ROMACT.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Around 30 cities and regions were engaged in activities, consisting of preparation work, including data collection and analysis, thematic workshops, study visits, exchange of information, opportunities for networking and developing partnerships, consultative work.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Other activities of the ROMACT The project ended in late 2014 with a major evaluation conference of cities and regions as well as local, national and international stakeholders.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Alliance has its own website with more information on its activities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The ONE in FIVE Campaign of the Council of Europe sets out to promote the signature and ratification of the Council of Europe Convention on the Protection of Children against Sexual Exploitation and Sexual Abuse, also known as the Lanzarote Convention.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Campaign's goals are to make children aware of the gravity and different types of sexual violence and abuse, and to prevent them.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress is ensuring the local and regional dimensions of the Campaign and has launched a Pact of Towns and Regions to Stop Sexual Violence against Children.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Pact proposes the 'four Ps' approach: to prevent abuse, protect victims, prosecute perpetrators while ensuring the full participation of children in the entire process.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] All services and actions must be respectful of children's rights, put the child's best interest first, and enable children's voices to be heard, in order to deliver locally what children and families need to stop sexual violence and sexual abuse, as well as to bring perpetrators to justice.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress promotes this Pact with cities and regions and encourages them to sign and implement it in the field.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress has developed an institutional partnership with the Committee of the Regions (CoR) of the European Union, regular meetings and coordination between the respective members and secretariats take place.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The cooperation between the Congress and the Committee of the Regions is in place since the creation of the CoR in 1994.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] A 'Contact Group Congress/Committee of the Regions', that meets twice per year, was established in 1995.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Contact Group coordinates the two institutions' efforts and provides feedback on their activities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress and CoR members exchange views and implement common strategies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Since 2006 it is possible for members of the CoR to be part of an elections observation mission of the Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Nowadays, this happens systematically and members of the CoR are involved in the whole observation process.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The neighbouring states involved are often Member States of the Congress and the Congress is involved in activities of these entities, as well.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] More information on the cooperation between the Congress and the COR can be found on both the site of the Congress and on the site of the COR.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress is also involved with several organizations and associations of European municipalities and regions enhancing local and regional democracy by developing joint activities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Examples of these organizations are the Assembly of European Regions (AER), the Council of European Municipalities and Regions (CEMR), the Association of European Border Regions (AEBR) and the Conference of European Regional Legislative Assemblies (CALRE).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The Congress can be represented at meetings or events of these organizations and makes its policies and priorities known, in particular when they fall within the scope of these organisations' fields of activities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] National (and European) associations of local and regional authorities play a role in promoting local democracy which is vital to the work of the Congress of the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] They deliver information about Congress activities across to their countries, particularly by lobbying in their governments.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] They also, in some cases, play a part in the procedure whereby their country's national delegation to the Congress is designated.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] National associations play an active part in implementation of the provisions of the European Charter of Local Self-Government, denouncing abuses and possible violations and thus acting as an "early warning system"and a peaceful counterweight.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] The site of the Congress contains more information on national associations.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] International associations of local and regional authorities which have a consultative status with the Council of Europe also have observer status with the Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] Observer status may also be granted to other associations on application to the Bureau of the Congress..
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] This status gives them the right to take part in the work of the Congress, submit memoranda and comment on issues discussed at plenary sessions, but not to vote.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/congress-of-local-and-regional-authorities] One or more representatives of organizations with observer status may be invited to attend meetings of the Statutory Forum, the Bureau, the Committees or ad hoc working groups.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The **Council of Europe** (**CoE**; French: *Conseil de l'Europe*, **CdE**) is an international organisation which aims to uphold human rights, democracy and the rule of law in Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Founded in 1949, it is Europe's oldest intergovernmental organisation, representing 46 European member states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The council is an official United Nations observer.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] It operates with an annual ordinary budget of 656 million euros.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The organisation is distinct from the European Union (EU), although people sometimes confuse the two organisations – partly because the EU has adopted the original European flag, designed for the Council of Europe in 1955, as well as the European anthem.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] No country has ever joined the EU without first belonging to the Council of Europe, and it has been said that to see these interstate institutions of post-war Europe as clearly separate is "profoundly misleading".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Unlike the EU, the Council of Europe cannot make binding laws; however, the council has produced a number of international treaties, including the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Provisions from the convention are incorporated in domestic law in many participating countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The best-known body of the Council of Europe is the European Court of Human Rights, which rules on alleged violations of the ECHR.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The council's two statutory bodies are the Committee of Ministers, which comprises the foreign ministers of each member state, and the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe (PACE), which is composed of members of the national parliaments of each member state.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Commissioner for Human Rights is an institution within the Council of Europe, mandated to promote awareness of and respect for human rights within the member states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The secretary general presides over the secretariat of the organisation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Other major CoE bodies include the European Directorate for the Quality of Medicines & HealthCare (EDQM) and the European Audiovisual Observatory.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The headquarters of the Council of Europe, as well as the European Court of Human Rights, are situated in Strasbourg, France.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council uses English and French as its two official languages.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Committee of Ministers, the PACE, and the Congress of the Council of Europe also use German and Italian for some of their work.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The 1949 Statute of the Council of Europe established the organization, initially among Western European states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Portugal and Spain joined in 1976 and 1977 via the Portuguese and Spanish transitions to democracies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Following the revolutions of 1989 and dissolution of the Soviet Union, all post-Warsaw Pact and post-Yugoslav states countries joined (except Kosovo), as well as all European post-Soviet states except Belarus and Kazakhstan.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Russia became the first country expelled from the Council, following its 2022 invasion of Ukraine.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] In a speech in 1929, French Foreign Minister Aristide Briand floated the idea of an organisation which would gather European nations together in a "federal union" to resolve common problems.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The United Kingdom's wartime Prime Minister Winston Churchill first publicly suggested the creation of a "Council of Europe" in a BBC radio broadcast on 21 March 1943, while the Second World War was still raging.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] In his own words, he tried to "peer through the mists of the future to the end of the war", and think about how to rebuild and maintain peace on a shattered continent.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Given that Europe had been at the origin of two world wars, the creation of such a body would be, he suggested, "a stupendous business".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] He returned to the idea during a well-known speech at the University of Zurich on 19 September 1946, throwing the full weight of his considerable post-war prestige behind it.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Additionally, there were also many other statesmen and politicians across the continent, many of them members of the European Movement, who were quietly working towards the creation of the council.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Others again saw it as a nascent "United States of Europe", the resonant phrase that Churchill had reached for at Zurich in 1946.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The future structure of the Council of Europe was discussed at the Congress of Europe, which brought together several hundred leading politicians, government representatives and members of civil society in The Hague, Netherlands, in 1948.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Responding to the conclusions of the Congress of Europe, the Consultative Council of the Treaty of Brussels convened a Committee for the Study of European Unity, which met eight times from November 1948 to January 1949 to draw up the blueprint of a new broad-based European organisation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] There were two competing schools of thought: some favoured a classical international organisation with representatives of governments, while others preferred a political forum with parliamentarians.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Both approaches were finally combined through the creation of a Committee of Ministers (in which governments were represented) and a Consultative Assembly (in which parliaments were represented), the two main bodies mentioned in the Statute of the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] This dual intergovernmental and inter-parliamentary structure was later copied for the European Communities, NATO and OSCE.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council of Europe was signed into existence on 5 May 1949 by the Treaty of London, the organisation's founding Statute which set out the three basic values that should guide its work: democracy, human rights and the rule of law.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] It was signed in London on that day by ten states: Belgium, Denmark, France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Norway, Sweden and the United Kingdom, though Turkey and Greece joined three months later.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] On 10 August 1949, 100 members of the council's Consultative Assembly, parliamentarians drawn from the twelve member nations, met in Strasbourg for its first plenary session, held over 18 sittings and lasting nearly a month.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] In August 1949, Paul-Henri Spaak resigned as Belgium's foreign minister in order to be elected as the first president of the assembly.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Behind the scenes, he too had been quietly working towards the creation of the council, and played a key role in steering its early work.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] However, in December 1951, after nearly three years in the role, Spaak resigned in disappointment after the Assembly rejected proposals for a "European political authority".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Convinced that the Council of Europe was never going to be in a position to achieve his long-term goal of a unified Europe, he soon tried again in a new and more promising format, based this time on economic integration, becoming one of the founders of the European Union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] There was huge enthusiasm for the Council of Europe in its early years, as its pioneers set about drafting what was to become the European Convention on Human Rights, a charter of individual rights which – it was hoped – no member government could ever again violate.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] They drew, in part, on the tenets of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, signed only a few months earlier in Paris.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Today, this is the European Court of Human Rights, whose rulings are binding on 46 European nations, the most far-reaching system of international justice anywhere in the world.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Iceland had already joined in 1950, followed in 1956 by Austria, Cyprus in 1961, Switzerland in 1963 and Malta in 1965.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] In 2018, an archive of all speeches made to the PACE by heads of state or government since the Council of Europe's creation in 1949 appeared online, the fruit of a two-year project entitled "Voices of Europe".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] At the time of its launch, the archive comprised 263 speeches delivered over a 70-year period by some 216 presidents, prime ministers, monarchs and religious leaders from 45 countries – though it continues to expand, as new speeches are added every few months.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Some very early speeches by individuals considered to be "founding figures" of the European institutions, even if they were not heads of state or government at the time, are also included (such as Sir Winston Churchill or Robert Schuman).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The full text of the speeches is given in both English and French, regardless of the original language used.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The archive is searchable by country, by name, and chronologically.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Those conventions and decisions are developed by the member states working together at the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Both organisations function as concentric circles around the common foundations for European cooperation and harmony, with the Council of Europe being the geographically wider circle.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The European Union could be seen as the smaller circle with a much higher level of integration through the transfer of powers from the national to the EU level.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] "The Council of Europe and the European Union: different roles, shared values." Council of Europe conventions/treaties are also open for signature to non-member states, thus facilitating equal co-operation with countries outside Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council of Europe's most famous achievement is the European Convention on Human Rights, which was adopted in 1950 following a report by the PACE, and followed on from the United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Convention created the European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Court supervises compliance with the European Convention on Human Rights and thus functions as the highest European court.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] It is to this court that Europeans can bring cases if they believe that a member country has violated their fundamental rights and freedoms.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The various activities and achievements of the Council of Europe can be found in detail on its official website.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Occasionally the Council of Europe organises summits of the heads of state and government of its member states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Four summits have been held to date with the fourth concluding on 17 May 2023.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The seat of the Council of Europe is in Strasbourg, France.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] First meetings were held in Strasbourg's University Palace in 1949, but the Council of Europe soon moved into its own buildings.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Building in the area started in 1949 with the predecessor of the *Palais de l'Europe*, the Palace of Europe (demolished in 1977), and came to a provisional end in 2007 with the opening of the New General Office Building, later named "Agora", in 2008.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Palace of Europe and the Art Nouveau Villa Schutzenberger (seat of the European Audiovisual Observatory) are in the Orangerie district, and the European Court of Human Rights, the EDQM and the Agora Building are in the Robertsau district.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Agora building has been voted "best international business centre real estate project of 2007" on 13 March 2008, at the MIPIM 2008.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The European Youth Centre is located in the Wacken district.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Besides its headquarters in Strasbourg, the Council of Europe is also present in other cities and countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council of Europe Development Bank has its seat in Paris, the North-South Centre of the Council of Europe is established in Lisbon, Portugal, and the Centre for Modern Languages is in Graz, Austria.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] There are European Youth Centres in Budapest, Hungary, and in Strasbourg.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The European Wergeland Centre, a new Resource Centre on education for intercultural dialogue, human rights and democratic citizenship, operated in cooperation with the Norwegian Government, opened in Oslo, Norway, in February 2009.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council of Europe has external offices all over the European continent and beyond.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] There are four 'Programme Offices', namely in Ankara, Podgorica, Skopje, and Venice.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] There are also 'Council of Europe Offices' in Baku, Belgrade, Chisinau, Kyiv, Paris, Pristina, Sarajevo, Tbilisi, Tirana, and Yerevan.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Bucharest has a Council of Europe Office on Cybercrime.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] There are also Council of Europe Offices in non-European capital cities like Rabat and Tunis.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Since "European" is not defined in international law, the definition of "European" has been a question that has recurred during the CoE's history.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Turkey was admitted in 1950, although it is a transcontinental state that lies mostly in Asia, with a smaller portion in Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] In 1994, the PACE adopted Recommendation 1247, which said that admission to the CoE should be "in principle open only to states whose national territory lies wholly or partly in Europe"; later, however, the Assembly extended eligibility to apply and be admitted to Armenia, Azerbaijan and Georgia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council of Europe was founded on 5 May 1949 by Belgium, Denmark, France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Norway, Sweden and the United Kingdom.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Greece and Turkey joined three months later.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Iceland, West Germany and Saar Protectorate joined the Council of Europe as associate members in 1950.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] West Germany became a full member in 1951, and the Saar withdrew its application after it joined West Germany following the 1955 Saar Statute referendum.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Spain joined in 1977, two years after the death of its dictator Francisco Franco and the Spanish transition to democracy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Next to join were Liechtenstein (1978), San Marino (1988) and Finland (1989).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] After Russia's expulsion in 2022, the Council has 46 member states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Although most Council members are predominantly Christian in heritage, there are four Muslim-majority member states: Bosnia and Herzegovina, Turkey, Albania and Azerbaijan.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The CoE has granted some countries a status that allows them to participate in CoE activities without being full members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] There are three types of nonmember status: *associate member*, *special guest* and *observer*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Associate member status was created for former Axis states which had not yet regained their sovereignty since their defeat in the Second World War; as such, it is no longer used, although there have been proposals to reactivate it to permit enhanced participation by the current observer states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] "Special guest" status was used as a transitional status for post-Soviet countries that wished to join the council after the fall of the Berlin Wall and is no longer commonly used.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] "Observer" status is for non-European nations who accept democracy, rule of law, and human rights, and wish to participate in Council initiatives.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The United States became an observer state in 1995.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Currently, Canada, the Holy See, Japan, Mexico and the United States are observer states, while Israel is an observer to the PACE.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Additionally Kosovo is a member of the Council of Europe Development Bank and a member of the Council of Europe's Venice Commission.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Assembly of Kosovo was invited to take part in the work of the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe and its committees as an observer in 2016.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Two representatives of local government in Kosovo participate in the work of the Congress of Local and Regional Authorities as observers.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Statute of the Council of Europe provides for the voluntary suspension, involuntary suspension, and exclusion of members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Article 8 of the Statute provides that any member who has "seriously violated" Article 3 may be suspended from its rights of representation, and that the Committee of Ministers may request that such a member withdraws from the Council under Article 7.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] (The Statute does not define the "serious violation" phrase.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Under Article 8 of the Statute, if a member state fails to withdraw upon request, the Committee may terminate its membership, in consultation with the PACE.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council suspended Greece in 1967, after a military coup d'état, and the Greek junta withdrew from the CoE.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Greece was readmitted to the council in 1974.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Russia became a member of the Council of Europe in 1996.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] In 2014, after Russia annexed Crimea from Ukraine and supported separatists in eastern Ukraine, the Council stripped Russia of its voting rights in the PACE.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] In response, Russia began to boycott the Assembly in 2016, and beginning from 2017 ceased paying its annual membership dues of 32.6 million euros (US$37.1 million) to the Council placing the institution under financial strain.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Russia stated that its suspension by the council was unfair, and demanded the restoration of its voting rights.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Russia had threatened to withdraw from the Council unless its voting rights were restored in time for the election of a new secretary general.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] European Council secretary-general Thorbjørn Jagland organised a special committee to find a compromise with Russia in early 2018, a move that was criticised by some as giving in to alleged Russian pressure by Council members and academic observers, especially if voting sanctions were lifted.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] In June 2019, an approximately two-thirds majority of the Council voted (on a 118–62 vote, with 10 abstentions) to restore Russia's voting rights in the council.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Opponents of lifting the suspension included Ukraine and other post-Soviet countries, such as the Baltic states, who argued that readmission amounted to normalising Russia's malign activity.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Supporters of restoring Russia's council rights included France and Germany, which argued that a Russian withdrawal from the council would be harmful because it would deprive Russian citizens of their ability to initiate cases in the European Court of Human Rights.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] On 3 March 2022, after Russia launched a full-scale military invasion of Ukraine, the council suspended Russia for violations of the council's statute and the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The suspension blocked Russia from participation in the council's ministerial council, the PACE, and the Council of the Baltic Sea States, but still left Russia obligated to follow the ECHR.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] On 15 March 2022, hours before the vote to expel the country, Russia initiated a voluntary withdrawal procedure from the council.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Russian delegation planned to deliver its formal withdrawal on 31 December 2022, and announced its intent to denounce the ECHR.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] However, on the same day, the council's Committee of Ministers decided Russia's membership in the council would be terminated immediately, and determined that Russia had been removed from the Council under its exclusion mechanism rather than through the withdrawal mechanism.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] After being excluded from the Council of Europe, Russia's former president and prime minister Dmitry Medvedev endorsed restoring the death penalty in Russia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council of Europe works mainly through international treaties, usually called conventions in its system.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] By drafting conventions or international treaties, common legal standards are set for its member states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The conventions are collected in the European Treaty Series.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Several conventions have also been opened for signature to non-member states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Non-member states also participate in several partial agreements, such as the Venice Commission, the Group of States Against Corruption (GRECO), the European Pharmacopoeia Commission and the North-South Centre.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Cooperation between the European Union and the Council of Europe was reinforced in the mid-2000s, notably on culture and education as well as on the international enforcement of justice and Human Rights.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The European Union is expected to accede to the European Convention on Human Rights (the convention).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] 14 of the convention is designed to allow the EU to accede to it and the EU Treaty of Lisbon contains a protocol binding the EU to join.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The EU would thus be subject to its human rights law and external monitoring as its member states currently are.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council of Europe *Schools of Political Studies* were established to train future generations of political, economic, social and cultural leaders in countries in transition.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] With the participation of national and international experts, they run annual series of seminars and conferences on topics such as European integration, democracy, human rights, the rule of law and globalisation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The first School of Political Studies was created in Moscow in 1992.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] By 2020, 20 other schools had been set up along the same lines, forming an association; a network covering the whole of Eastern and South-Eastern Europe and the Caucasus, as well as some countries in the Southern Mediterranean region.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The schools are part of the Education Department, which is part of the Directorate of Democratic Participation within the Directorate General of Democracy ("DGII") of the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Cooperation between the CoE and the UN started with the agreement signed by the Secretariats of these institutions on 15 December 1951.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] On 17 October 1989, the General Assembly of the United Nations approved a resolution on granting observer status to the Council of Europe which was proposed by several member states of the CoE.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Currently, the Council of Europe holds observer status with the United Nations and is regularly represented in the UN General Assembly.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] It has organised the regional UN conferences against racism and on women.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] It co-operates with the United Nations at many levels, in particular in the areas of human rights, minorities, migration and counter-terrorism.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Non-governmental organisations (NGOs) can participate in the INGOs Conference of the Council of Europe and become observers to inter-governmental committees of experts.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council of Europe drafted the European Convention on the Recognition of the Legal Personality of International Non-Governmental Organisations in 1986, which sets the legal basis for the existence and work of NGOs in Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Article 11 of the European Convention on Human Rights protects the right to freedom of association, which is also a fundamental norm for NGOs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The rules for consultative status for INGOs appended to the resolution (93)38 "On relation between the Council of Europe and non-governmental organisations", adopted by the Committee of Ministers on 18 October 1993 at the 500th meeting of the Ministers' Deputies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] On 30 May 2018, the Council of Europe signed a memorandum of understanding with the European football confederation UEFA.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council of Europe also signed an agreement with FIFA in which the two agreed to strengthen future cooperation in areas of common interests.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The deal which included cooperation between member states in the sport of football and safety and security at football matches was finalised in October 2018.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The General Agreement on Privileges and Immunities of the Council of Europe grants the organisation certain privileges and immunities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The working conditions of staff are governed by the council's staff regulations, which are public.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Salaries and emoluments paid by the Council of Europe to its officials are tax-exempt on the basis of Article 18 of the General Agreement on Privileges and Immunities of the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The Council of Europe created, and has since 1955 used as its official symbol, the European Flag with 12 golden stars arranged in a circle on a blue background.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] Its musical anthem since 1972, the "European anthem", is based on the "Ode to Joy" theme from Ludwig van Beethoven's ninth symphony.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] On 5 May 1964, the 15th anniversary of its founding, the Council of Europe established 5 May as Europe Day.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The wide private and public use of the European Flag is encouraged to symbolise a European dimension.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] To avoid confusion with the European Union which subsequently adopted the same flag in the 1980s, as well as other European institutions, the Council of Europe often uses a modified version with a lower-case "e" surrounding the stars which are referred to as the "Council of Europe Logo".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] In October 2022, a new and different Pan-European meeting of 44 states was held, as the "inaugural summit of the European Political Community", a new forum largely organised by French President Emmanuel Macron.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] After Azerbaijan joined the CoE in 2001, both the Council and its Parliamentary Assembly were criticised for having a weak response to election rigging and human rights violations in Azerbaijan.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] An internal inquiry was set up in 2017 amid allegations of bribery by Azerbaijan government officials and criticism of "caviar diplomacy" at the council.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] A 219-page report was issued in 2018 after a ten-month investigation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] The inquiry also named Italian member Luca Volontè as a suspect in "activities of a corruptive nature".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/council-of-europe] In 2021, Volontè was convicted of accepting bribes from Azerbaijani officials to water down critiques of the nation's human rights record, and he was sentenced by a court in Milan to four years in prison.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t/damien-cottier] He holds a diploma in international relations from the Graduate Institute of International Studies in Geneva, and a master's in history, geography and political science from the University of Neuchatel.
